# Commit Messages

Commit messages must follow the Conventional Commits specification.

The format is:
```
<type>[optional scope]: <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

Types include:
- `feat`: A new feature
- `fix`: A bug fix
- `docs`: Documentation only changes
- `style`: Changes that do not affect the meaning of the code (white-space, formatting, missing semi-colons, etc)
- `refactor`: A code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature
- `perf`: A code change that improves performance
- `test`: Adding missing tests or correcting existing tests
- `build`: Changes that affect the build system or external dependencies
- `ci`: Changes to CI configuration files and scripts
- `chore`: Other changes that don't modify src or test files
- `revert`: Reverts a previous commit

Example:
```
feat(auth): add user login functionality

Implement JWT-based authentication with refresh tokens.
Add login endpoint at /api/auth/login.

Closes #123
```

## Commit Validation
I must validate the commit message before any commit to ensure it follows the Conventional Commits specification.
I must always ask the user for approval before committing to confirm they are fine with the commit message.
Before committing, I MUST perform all pre-commit security checks (see security.mdc) and verify that `PRODUCTION_SECURITY_CHECKLIST.md` is up-to-date if security-related files were changed.

## Pre-Commit Hooks

The project uses pre-commit hooks to ensure code quality and security before commits.

### Setup
1. Install pre-commit: `pip install pre-commit` or `pip3 install pre-commit`
2. Install hooks: `pre-commit install`
3. Install commit-msg hook: `pre-commit install --hook-type commit-msg`
4. Initialize secrets baseline (if not exists): `detect-secrets scan > .secrets.baseline`
5. (Optional) Run on all files: `pre-commit run --all-files`

### Pre-Commit Checks
The following checks run automatically before each commit:

#### General File Checks
- Trailing whitespace removal
- End of file fixer
- YAML/JSON/TOML validation
- Large file detection (max 1MB)
- Merge conflict detection
- Case conflict detection
- Mixed line ending detection (enforces LF)
- Private key detection
- AWS credentials detection
- Secret detection

#### Commit Message Validation
- Validates commit messages follow Conventional Commits specification
- Checks commit type (feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, perf, test, build, ci, chore, revert)
- Validates subject case (lower-case)
- Allows any scope

#### PHP Code Checks
- PHP syntax validation on all PHP files
- Runs via Docker container to ensure consistency

#### Security Checks
- Detects `.env` files being committed
- Detects debug code (var_dump, print_r, dd, dump, console.log)
- Detects potential hardcoded secrets (passwords, API keys, tokens)
- Uses detect-secrets tool for comprehensive secret scanning

### Manual Execution
- Run on staged files: `pre-commit run`
- Run on all files: `pre-commit run --all-files`
- Run specific hook: `pre-commit run <hook-id>`
- Skip hooks (not recommended): `git commit --no-verify`

### Bypassing Pre-Commit Hooks
Pre-commit hooks should NOT be bypassed unless absolutely necessary. If bypassing is required:
- Use `git commit --no-verify` sparingly
- Document the reason for bypassing
- Ensure security checks are performed manually
- Fix issues before pushing to remote
